<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
    Farcom hybrid connectivity note:

    By default (targetSdk >= 28) Android blocks all cleartext (non-TLS) HTTP traffic.
    That's the right default when only talking to fixed, known Internet hosts. Farcom is
    different: a self-hosted/LAN deployment's server address is arbitrary and chosen by
    the user at runtime (127.0.0.1, 192.168.x.x, 10.x.x.x, a local hostname, ...), and
    Android's network-security-config can only allow-list exact hostnames/IPs, not IP
    ranges - so there is no way to allow "any private LAN address" without allowing
    cleartext generally.

    We allow cleartext HTTP app-wide as a result. This affects only HTTP(S)-based
    features (e.g. the file transfer server URL) - SIP signaling transport (UDP/TCP/TLS)
    is chosen independently on the login screen and is unaffected by this file.

    Deployers who want to enforce TLS everywhere should run their central/self-hosted
    server with a valid certificate (e.g. via a local CA + mkcert for LAN) and remove
    this override, or replace it with a domain-config allow-list of their specific
    server hostname(s).
-->
<network-security-config>
    <base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="true" />
</network-security-config>
